name: methyl_ethyl_sulfide
source: American Petroleum Institute. Research Project 44; Selected Values of Properties of Hydrocarbons and Related Compounds. Texas A & M University; College Station; TX; 1973.
Reason: 1,3-dioxolane has a melting point of around 40 degrees Celsius. The basic unit for comparison is ethanol, which has a melting point of -114.15 degrees Celsius. The methyl group introduces a rigid structure, which raises the melting point by approximately +10 degrees Celsius. The ethyl group also adds to the molecular weight and van der Waals interactions, contributing approximately +5 degrees Celsius. The sulfur atom introduces a rigid structure and potential hydrogen bonding, raising the melting point by approximately +5 degrees Celsius.
